1	1	ed2fbfa1-28fd-4e0f-8e5a-25240eaec5d1	["customer / account / loan id", "dpd_bucket", "outstanding_amount", "amount_due", "due_date"]	["conversation_history"]	[]	ROLE\nYou are Collections Analyst AI.\n\nPrimary objective\nAnalyze each customer’s current delinquency situation and identify the most effective path to bring them back to a consistent, on-time repayment schedule.\n\nGoal\nRecommend the next best action we should take for the customer, in alignment with the SOP provided below.\n\nInputs available\nYou may be given (for each customer) any combination of:\nInputs you may receive (any subset)\nPayment & delinquency history: due dates, DPD, repayments, partial payments, reversals/chargebacks, frequency, amount patterns, promises-to-pay, broken PTPs.\nConversation logs (call/chat/email): stated hardship, job loss, medical/family issues, disputes, sentiment, avoidance, commitment, dates mentioned, requested payment plans.\nIncome & employment: employer, job type, tenure, salary/income range, pay frequency, bank credits if provided, verification status, last update date.\nCredit bureau: score, tradelines, utilization, recent inquiries, delinquencies, write-offs, total obligations, estimated installment burden, public records (if provided), last pull date.\n\nKey instructions for interpreting input data\nDate and relevance filter\nCurrent date: {{current_date}}\nReview only tickets and conversations from the last 180 days.\nIgnore any conversations older than 180 days.\nAlso ignore content within the last 180 days if it is not relevant to the customer’s current situation.\nRecency check before recommending outreach\nBefore proposing any outreach, review ticket history for the last 7 days:\nIf an email was sent within the last 7 days and there is no customer response and no completed survey, you should generally recommend no action to avoid over-contacting.\nException: If the due date is very close or the situation is urgent, recommend an urgent outreach and explain why.\nPayment failure detection: Actively look for payment failures (in payment data and/or mentioned in conversations) that could be preventing repayment (e.g., repeated failed attempts, mandate/autopay issues, insufficient funds, bank errors). If present, call this out explicitly and incorporate it into the recommended next step.\nNon-negotiable constraint: No hallucinations: Do not create, assume, or infer missing facts as truth.Use only the information provided; if something is unknown, state it as unknown and reduce confidence accordingly.\nHOW to go about analyzing the data (for every customers)\nRules you must follow\nDO NOT HALLUCINATE , Use only evidence in the case. Do not invent facts.\nWeight by recency: prefer newer signals. If something is old, discount it and say so.\nIf key data is missing, degrade gracefully: \nIf signals conflict (e.g., bureau strong but payment history weak), reconcile explicitly and state the most plausible explanation(s).\nDo not output sensitive attributes or make prohibited inferences. Stick to financial capacity and documented facts.\n\nFoundation to a collection analysis is analyzing the following for each customer\nVulnerability: any customer condition or circumstance that materially reduces their ability to engage with collections normally or increases the risk of harm if we use standard collection tactics (frequency, tone, deadlines, escalation). It’s less about “can they pay” and more about duty of care + appropriate treatment.\nAffordability: i.e how much the customer can pay us in the upcoming month\nWillingness: is the customer willing to pay us, or are they willfully trying to avoid the payment\n\nVulnerability: TRUE/ FALSE\n\nA customer is vulnerable if there is credible evidence (from customer statements or verified records) of one or more of the following:\nHealth / mental capacity: mental health crisis, suicidal ideation, psychiatric care, serious illness/hospitalization, cognitive impairment/disability affecting communication or decisions, pregnancy/post-partum complications.\nBereavement: customer deceased or death of a close family member.\nSevere accident / safety risk: major injury (customer/dependent), domestic violence/abuse disclosure.\nLegal / exceptional service status: active military deployment/war-zone constraints, incarceration or legal restrictions that materially limit engagement.\nExploitation / loss of control: fraud/scam victim, coerced payments/financial abuse, or concerning third-party control over communication/payments.\n\n\nAffordability\nYour task is to assess the customer’s Affordability for next month using only the information provided in this case. Data coverage varies by customer—some cases may include payment history, conversation notes, income/employment information, and/or credit bureau data, while others may include only a subset (sometimes only payment history). Data may vary in freshness: some inputs may be from today, while others may be up to 6 months old.\n\nCore objective (must do)\nEstimate what the customer can realistically pay us next month as a single recommended amount and a range (low–high).\nAssign an Affordability label using the formula below, based on the customer’s estimated next-month pay capacity vs the Minimum Amount Due (MAD).\n\nReliability & recency rules (follow strictly)\nMost recent evidence wins. Prefer signals from the last 30–90 days over older signals.\nIf last 3 months of payments exist, they are a primary anchor and must be summarized and used.\nWhen stronger external data (e.g., verified income/employment) is not available, treat the customer’s statements in conversation as credible, unless contradicted by more reliable and more recent evidence.\nIf evidence conflicts, explicitly state which evidence you trusted and why (recency + reliability).\n\nEvidence you MUST use (if present)\n1) Last 3 months payments (required if available)\nList the payments for each of the last 3 months (amount + date if available).\nIdentify the pattern: stable / improving / deteriorating / irregular / no payments.\nUse this as a baseline to estimate next-month ability.\n\n2) Conversation signals (required if available)\nExtract and use any relevant disclosures, including:\nemployment/income status changes (job loss, new job start date, internship unpaid/low-paid)\nsevere financial distress indicators\nmajor expenses or shocks\nwillingness/intent and timing (“can pay after salary on X date”)\nTranslate these into an adjustment to next-month pay capacity.\n\n3) Verified income/employment or bureau data (if present)\nUse verified income/employment as strong evidence.\nUse bureau data as supporting context, not a replacement for recent payments + conversation.\nNext-month pay capacity estimation (required)\nEstimate Next-Month Pay Capacity (NMPC) = the amount the customer can realistically pay us next month.\n\nUse this hierarchy:\nIf last 3 months payments exist:\nStart baseline = median of the last 3 monthly payments (if only 2 months, use average; if 1 month, use that month).\nAdjust up/down based on recent conversation and verified changes impacting next month (e.g., job loss ↓, salary starting next month ↑).\nIf last 3 months payments do not exist:\nUse conversation + any income info to estimate a conservative NMPC.\nIf there is credible evidence the customer cannot pay anything next month, set NMPC = 0.\nDo not invent missing numbers. If NMPC can’t be inferred, return NOT SURE.\n\nAffordability label formula (must follow exactly)\nLet MAD = Minimum Amount Due (from case data). Compare NMPC to MAD:\nHIGH: NMPC > MAD\nMEDIUM: NMPC ≥ 60% of MAD and < MAD\nLOW: NMPC < 60% of MAD\nVERY LOW: NMPC = 0 OR NMPC < 10% of MAD\nNOT SURE: Not enough data to estimate NMPC or MAD not provided\nImportant: If MAD is missing, you must output NOT SURE (and still provide your best NMPC estimate if possible, clearly marked as an estimate).\n\nAbility to Pay (ATP)\nAdditionally we can estimate ability to pay: estimated amount the customer can pay next month to us depending upon what the customer has mentioned, payment history and income and employment data - depending on what is available to pay - some logic as we put for affordability only difference is Ability to pay is a number\n\n\nWillingness  (WTP) \nYou are a senior collections behavioral risk analyst at an education lender. Your task is to determine the customer’s Willingness to Pay (WTP) using only the data provided in this case. Data availability varies: some customers may have conversation logs + payment history + bureau + income/employment, while others may have only payment history. Data freshness varies: some fields may be today, others may be up to 6 months old. You must weight signals by recency, avoid guessing, and explicitly state uncertainty when evidence is limited.\nDefinition\nWillingness to Pay (WTP) = the customer’s intent and behavioral likelihood of paying given their situation, measured via existence of historical payments, the more the better, responsiveness, follow-through, consistency, cooperation, and avoidance—not their financial capacity.\nWillingness to Pay (WTP)\nAssign WTP level based on recent behavior:\nHIGH: responsive + consistent + follows through; payments align with promises when capacity exists\nMEDIUM;: mixed responsiveness or occasional broken promises; some payments\nLOW: Very irregular engagements but some sort of communication established between our agents and customers during the collection period\nVERY LOW: avoidance/ghosting, not at all engaging on any channels, repeated broken PTP, inconsistent reasons, no payments despite contact (especially if ability to pay not clearly constrained)\nNOT SURE: If there is not enough data to infer anything\n\n\n\nDetermining the next best action\n\nIf the customer is vulnerable: true then populate all information around the problem customer is facing and all but in propose a solution : we should strictly mention “agent review”\n\nIf the customer is not vulnerable && Affordability= HIGH\nWe should encourage them to pay then we should encourage to pay more minimum amount so as to clear arrears and mention why timely payments is good so as to build a health credit report etc .\nIf the customer ability to pay is so high that if they pay that much then they can clear Arreas in the next 3 months then we should ask them to pay that much amount and mention how that would clear up arrears and bring their credit report to very healthy place and why that is important\n\n\nIf customer is not vulnerable && Affordability= MEDIUM && Willingness: High or medium or low\nwe should encourage them to pay then we should encourage to trying paying close to minimum amount due and mention why timely payments is good so as to build a health credit report etc .\n\n\nIf customer is not vulnerable && Affordability= MEDIUM && Willingness: very low\nwe should encourage them to pay then we should ask them to  paying close to minimum amount due and mention a) they need to engage with us to help us help them b) not paying on time can be detrimental to credit report health and can have long term ramification\n\n\nIf customer is not vulnerable && Affordability= LOW && Willingness: High or medium or low\nWe should look at offering loan modification to reduce the installment amount right now for a period of a year or so giving enough time for student to find a job and then EMI kicking after that period is exhaused\n\n\nIf customer is not vulnerable && Affordability= LOW && Willingness: very low\nwe should encourage them to pay then we should ask them to  paying close to minimum amount due and mention a) they need to engage with us to help us help them b) not paying on time can be detrimental to credit report health and can have long term ramification\n\nIf customer is not vulnerable && Affordability= Very LOW && Willingness: High or medium or low\nWe should offer Foreberance of 3 months either ask them to pay a very small or no amount to reduce the burden on them and allow them  to focus on finding a new job and then EMI kicking after that period is exhausted\n\n\nIf customer is not vulnerable && Affordability= Very LOW && Willingness: very low\nwe should encourage them to pay then we should ask them to  paying close to minimum amount due and mention a) they need to engage with us to help us help them b) not paying on time can be detrimental to credit report health and can have long term ramification for them\n\n\n	{\n  "customer_guid": "string",\n   payment history : last 3 months payment history summarized in <=3 lines\n   conversation: last 6 months conversation summarized in <=3 lines relevant for the next best action in collections\n   Vulnerability: true/false,\n   if vulnerability true then give reason for vulnerability: "string (max 5 lines)",\n   Affordability: high/medium/low/very low/ not sure,\n   reason for affordability: "string (max 5 lines)",\n   Willingness: high/medium/low/very low/ not sure,\n   reason for Willingness: "string (max 5 lines)",\n   "ability_to_pay": value,\n  "reason_for_ability_to_pay": "string (max 5 lines)",\n  "problem_customr is facing": "string (max 5 lines)",\n  "problem_confidence_score": 1-10, (Confidence in problem identification (1-10). High (8-10): Explicit, recent, corroborated by multiple data points. Medium (5-7): Inferred from patterns, partially supported. Low (1-4): Weak evidence or outdated data"\n  "problem_evidence": "string (max 5 lines)",\n  "proposed_solution": "string (max 5 lines)",\n  "solution_confidence_score": 1-10, Confidence in solution (1-10). High (8-10): Directly aligned to confirmed problem, high success likelihood. Medium (5-7): Reasonable standard solution, moderate uncertainty. Low (1-4): Uncertain or speculative approach"\n  "solution_evidence": "string (max 5 lines)",\n\n  "proposed_email_to_customer": "Subject: ... Body: ... OR NO_ACTION" \n      "type": "string",\n      "description": "Customer email (≤10 lines). If email required to advance solution: output 'Subject: ...' and 'Body: ...'. If no email needed (internal monitoring, escalation): output 'NO_ACTION'. Use communication_guidelines for tone. When to send an email (use judgment): Request info (internship offer letter, bank details, start date); Answer their question plainly and completely; Acknowledge hardship, apologize if we caused frustration, outline help; Share good news (back to 'on schedule', fee waived, promise kept); Reinforce good behavior (keep current payment pattern to stay on track); Inform next steps we're taking and what we need from them; Re-engage a silent customer with clear, respectful nudge to respond; OR use your knowledge of education loan servicing what we can achieve via email with that customer"\n    },\n\n}	2026-02-25 12:42:02.163136	2026-04-06 08:33:37.063	[]	88bb298f-0fd9-407b-ad75-1ed7ae2ac794	["loan_account", "payment_history", "conversation_history"]	{"loan_account": {"docType": "tabular", "fileName": "test data-Beacon Demo - Loans data.csv", "fileSize": 225, "uploadedAt": "2026-04-06T08:26:20.910Z", "fieldAnalysis": [{"ignored": false, "fieldName": "customer / account / loan id", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "This field serves as the unique identifier for a specific loan account. It is the primary key used to track an individual customer's debt throughout the collections process.", "beaconsUnderstanding": "This field serves as the unique identifier for a specific loan account. It is the primary key used to track an individual customer's debt throughout the collections process."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "dpd_bucket", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "'DPD' stands for 'Days Past Due.' This field categorizes the delinquency of an account into specific timeframes (e.g., 60, 90, 150 days), which is essential for segmenting and prioritizing collection strategies."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "amount_due", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "This represents the total outstanding amount required to bring the account completely current. It likely includes all overdue principal, interest, and any accumulated fees."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "minimum_due", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "This is the minimum payment the borrower needs to make by the due date to prevent the account from becoming more delinquent. This amount is typically less than the total 'amount_due'."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "due_date", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "This is the date the most recent payment was due. Since these accounts are in collections, this date has already passed, triggering the delinquency status indicated by the 'dpd_bucket'."}]}, "payment_history": {"docType": "tabular", "fileName": "test data-Beacon Demo - Payments.csv", "fileSize": 1336, "uploadedAt": "2026-04-06T08:33:01.906Z", "fieldAnalysis": [{"ignored": false, "fieldName": "customer / account / loan id", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A unique identifier linking the payment record to a specific customer, account, or loan. This is the primary key for connecting this payment data with other account-level information."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "payment_reference", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A unique identifier for the specific payment transaction itself. It is used to track an individual payment attempt within the payment processing system."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "date_of_payment", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The date on which the payment was attempted or processed. This is crucial for tracking payment attempts against due dates and calculating delinquency."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "amount_paid", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The monetary value of the payment transaction. This amount is compared against the scheduled payment or outstanding balance to determine if it is a full or partial payment."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "payment_status", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "Indicates the outcome of the payment attempt, such as 'Success' or 'Failed'. This is critical for distinguishing between payments that reduce debt and those that require follow-up action."}]}, "conversation_history": {"docType": "tabular", "fileName": "test data-Beacon Demo - Conversation data.csv", "fileSize": 26726, "uploadedAt": "2026-04-06T08:33:23.181Z", "fieldAnalysis": [{"ignored": false, "fieldName": "customer / account / loan id", "confidence": "Medium", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A unique identifier that links the communication record to a specific customer, account, or loan. This is the primary key used to associate this conversation history with a specific debt being collected."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "date_and_timestamp", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The specific date and time when the communication event was sent or received. This is essential for creating an accurate chronological record of all collection activities."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "message_content", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The full text content of the message exchanged between the collections agent and the customer. This provides the context for the interaction, including any agreements, disputes, or information requested."}]}}
4	\N	3fc91ebc-a89e-4154-9d62-3c49d6444be4	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	2026-04-08 15:05:34.561359	2026-04-08 15:05:34.561359	[]	dcc2126a-3c88-4d77-a07f-8c62304d6bdb	["loan_account"]	{"loan_account": {"docType": "tabular", "fileName": "test - Sheet1 (1).csv", "fileSize": 2704, "uploadedAt": "2026-04-08T15:05:23.597Z", "fieldAnalysis": [{"ignored": false, "fieldName": "customer_id", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A unique identifier assigned to each customer. This ID is used to link loan account data to other customer information across the platform, such as contact details or other products."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "arrears_months", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The number of consecutive months the account has been in arrears, indicating how many contractual payments have been missed. This is a primary measure of delinquency severity used for collections segmentation."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "arrears_balance_gbp", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The total outstanding overdue amount on the account, expressed in GBP. This is a core metric for prioritising collections activity and assessing the financial risk of the account."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "monthly_contractual_payment_gbp", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The fixed monthly payment amount the customer is contractually required to pay, expressed in GBP. This amount is the baseline used to calculate arrears when payments are missed or underpaid."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "disposable_income_gbp", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The customer's monthly disposable income, likely captured during an Income and Expenditure (IE) assessment. This is a critical data point for assessing affordability and structuring sustainable repayment plans."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "vulnerability_rag", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A Red/Amber/Green (RAG) status that summarises the severity of a customer's identified vulnerability. This is used to flag accounts for specialised handling and to apply appropriate support measures."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "vulnerability_type", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "Specifies the nature of the customer's vulnerability, such as health or domestic issues. This detailed information is essential for tailoring support and communication strategies in a compliant and empathetic manner."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "forbearance_in_last_6_months", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A flag indicating if the account has been subject to a forbearance measure (e.g., payment plan, deferral) within the previous six months. This helps to understand the customer's recent financial history and the effectiveness of prior support."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "prior_forbearance_type", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "Describes the type of the most recent forbearance arrangement applied to the account. This context helps in deciding future support options and identifying patterns of financial difficulty."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "consecutive_payment_plans", "confidence": "Medium", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A count of the number of back-to-back payment plans the customer has entered. This can signal persistent financial difficulty, suggesting that short-term forbearance may be insufficient."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "active_insolvency", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A flag indicating if the customer is currently in a formal insolvency process like an IVA, DRO, or bankruptcy. An active insolvency legally restricts collections activity and dictates how the debt must be managed."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "active_dca_placement", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "Indicates whether the account has been outsourced to an external Debt Collection Agency (DCA) for management. This determines which party is responsible for customer contact and collections efforts."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "breathing_space_active", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A flag indicating if the customer is currently protected by a statutory Breathing Space period. This is a critical operational flag that legally requires a pause on most collections and enforcement activity."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "breathing_space_ref", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The unique reference number for a customer's active Breathing Space case. This ID is used for tracking, auditing, and managing the account during the protected period."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "ie_assessment_completed", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A flag indicating whether a formal Income and Expenditure (IE) assessment has been completed with the customer. The completion of an IE is a key step before agreeing to a sustainable forbearance arrangement."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "priority_bills_up_to_date", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "Indicates whether the customer has reported being current on their priority debts (e.g., rent, utilities). This information, gathered during an affordability assessment, provides crucial context on their overall financial stability."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "financial_difficulty_duration", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A classification of the likely duration of the customer's financial problems. This helps determine whether short-term forbearance or a longer-term solution is more appropriate."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "payment_affordability_level", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "An assessment of the customer's current ability to make payments against their contractual amount. This directly informs the type of payment arrangement that can be offered."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "contacts_whilst_in_arrears", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A count of contact attempts made to the customer since the account first entered arrears. This metric is used to monitor contact strategy intensity and ensure adherence to fair treatment regulations."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "date_last_contact", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "The date of the last recorded communication or attempted contact with the customer. This field is essential for managing contact frequency and scheduling follow-up activities."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "outbound_comms_sent", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A count of outbound communications (e.g., calls, emails, letters) sent to the customer over a given period. This is used to measure the level of contact activity as part of a collections strategy."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "inbound_comms_received", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "A count of inbound communications received from the customer, which serves as a key measure of customer engagement. High inbound contact may signal a willingness to resolve the debt or a service issue."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "worse_CAIS_status", "confidence": "High", "userDescription": "", "beaconsUnderstanding": "Represents the most severe arrears status reported for this account to credit bureaus under the Credit Account Information Sharing (CAIS) framework. The codes (e.g., 1-6 for arrears, 8 for default) are a standardized measure of credit performance."}]}}
3	\N	0fca104f-a7aa-4aa1-99b6-0ebf95f6d2b4	[]	[]	[]	\N	\N	2026-04-08 14:57:13.186382	2026-04-09 08:22:46.196	[]	f8e55a8d-ff5b-4fc5-9e1f-f5ef1564e309	["loan_account"]	{"loan_account": {"docType": "tabular", "fileName": "test - Sheet1 (1).csv", "fileSize": 2704, "uploadedAt": "2026-04-09T08:22:28.531Z", "fieldAnalysis": [{"ignored": false, "fieldName": "customer_id", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["CUST-001", "CUST-002", "CUST-003", "CUST-004"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "A unique identifier for the customer associated with the loan account. This is used to link this account data to other customer-level information like contact details or other products."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "arrears_months", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["1", "3", "6", "2"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The number of months the account has been in arrears, indicating the duration of delinquency. This is a key metric for segmenting collections strategies and assessing the risk of default."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "arrears_balance_gbp", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["320", "960", "1920", "640"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The total overdue amount on the loan account, expressed in GBP. This is a primary measure of arrears severity, used to prioritise collections activity and calculate potential losses."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "monthly_contractual_payment_gbp", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["320"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The regular monthly payment amount contractually agreed upon for the loan, expressed in GBP. This serves as a baseline for calculating arrears and assessing payment affordability."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "disposable_income_gbp", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["280", "95", "0", "850"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The customer's reported monthly disposable income, expressed in GBP, likely captured during an Income and Expenditure (IE) assessment. This is crucial for determining an affordable and sustainable repayment plan."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "vulnerability_rag", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["None", "Red", "Amber"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "A Red/Amber/Green (RAG) status indicator summarising the severity of a customer's identified vulnerability. This allows for quick triaging of cases to ensure appropriate handling and support."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "vulnerability_type", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["None", "Suicidal ideation", "Terminal illness", "Mental health — anxiety"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The specific category of vulnerability identified for the customer. This provides essential context for tailoring communication, applying appropriate forbearance, and ensuring compliance with regulatory expectations."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "forbearance_in_last_6_months", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["No", "Yes"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "A flag indicating whether the account has had any forbearance measures, such as a payment plan or deferral, applied within the last six months. This helps assess the recent history of financial difficulty."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "prior_forbearance_type", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["None", "Payment Plan"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The type of the most recent forbearance arrangement applied to the account. This field gives insight into what kind of support, such as a Payment Plan, has been previously attempted."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "consecutive_payment_plans", "confidence": "Medium", "sampleValues": ["0", "1", "2"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "A counter for how many consecutive payment plans the customer has been on. This metric helps identify customers in a cycle of recurring difficulty who may need a more sustainable solution."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "active_insolvency", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["No", "Yes"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "A flag indicating if the customer is currently in an active insolvency proceeding like an IVA, DRO, or bankruptcy. This status legally restricts collections activities and requires a specific handling process."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "active_dca_placement", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["No"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "A flag indicating if the account is currently placed with an external Debt Collection Agency (DCA) for recovery. This determines whether collections activities are managed internally or by a third party."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "breathing_space_active", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["No", "Yes"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "An indicator showing whether the customer is currently in an approved Breathing Space protection period. This is a critical status as it legally halts most collections contact and enforcement actions."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "breathing_space_ref", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["BS-2025-44821"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The unique reference number for an active Breathing Space case. This identifier is used for tracking and administration of the protection period."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "ie_assessment_completed", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["Yes", "No"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "A flag indicating whether a formal Income and Expenditure (IE) assessment has been completed for the customer. A completed IE is often a prerequisite for setting up a sustainable forbearance plan."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "priority_bills_up_to_date", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["Yes", "No"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The customer's self-reported status on whether they are current with priority bills (e.g., mortgage, rent). This is a key part of an affordability assessment to gauge the severity of their financial situation."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "financial_difficulty_duration", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["Short-term", "Medium-term", "Long-term"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "An assessment of the expected duration of the customer's financial difficulty. This categorization helps decide whether a short-term arrangement or a more durable, long-term solution is appropriate."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "payment_affordability_level", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["Full", "Partial", "None"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "A classification of the customer's ability to make payments towards their arrears, based on an affordability assessment. This segmentation directly drives the type of payment arrangement offered."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "contacts_whilst_in_arrears", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["3", "7", "12", "14"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The total number of contact attempts made to the customer since their account entered arrears. This metric can be used to monitor contact strategy effectiveness and ensure compliance with rules on excessive contact."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "date_last_contact", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["2025-06-10", "2025-06-08", "2025-06-12", "2025-06-11"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The date of the last recorded contact attempt with the customer. This field is essential for managing contact cadences and ensuring customers are not contacted too frequently or infrequently."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "outbound_comms_sent", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["2", "5", "8", "9"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The count of outbound communications, such as emails or SMS, sent to the customer. This helps measure the intensity and cost of the collections outreach strategy."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "inbound_comms_received", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["1", "2", "4", "5"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The count of inbound communications received from the customer. This can be a key indicator of customer engagement and their proactivity in addressing their financial situation."}, {"ignored": false, "fieldName": "worse_CAIS_status", "confidence": "High", "sampleValues": ["1", "0", "2", "8"], "beaconsUnderstanding": "The worst delinquency status reported for this account to credit bureaus via Credit Account Information Sharing (CAIS). The numeric codes (e.g., 1=one month in arrears, 8=default) represent arrears severity on the credit file."}]}}
